title.narrative: CHILD WELL-BEING & Early Child Development (ECD)

description.narrative: Strengthened capacity at central and municipal levels for scaling up of Home visiting scheme as a part of the decentralized family medicine systems for provision of quality maternal health, and child health and wellbeing services, particularly for the most vulnerable children including Kosovo Serbs in collaboration with education and child protection sectors, which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Children With Disabilities, Cross-Sectoral Early Childhood Development, Early Childhood Development, Early Childhood Development (Covid), Early Learning, Health Systems Strengthening, Immunization, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Learning Outcomes, Maternal And Newborn Health, Micronutrients, Other Cross-Sectoral Programme Areas, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, more children with disabilities as well as from Roma, Ashkali and Egyptian communities, as well as Kosovo-Albanians and Kosovo Serbs have access to and utilize a quality continuum of health care and quality education services

description.narrative: The Universal Progressive Home Visiting programme shifted to virtual implementation in line with COVID-19 restriction measures. Through UNICEF support, 781 health professionals were equipped with digital skills and child development approaches for the implementation of telehealth counselling during the COVID-19 pandemic. UNICEF supported the assessment of Cold Chain Equipment which provided key recommendations to support Kosovo institutions for preparedness and smooth deployment of the COVID-19 vaccine. To facilitate distance learning for children age 0-6 years, 1,500 (88%) early learning educators were equipped with skills and knowledge on online early childhood development and 418 (24%) educators in inclusive early education. | Status:Met | As-of Date:18/01/2021
